Dutch chemicals group AkzoNV &lt;AKZO.AS> said it hoped to consolidate its core activitiesthis year by making small acquisitions in the US.   Akzo chairman Aarnoud Loudon told a news conference on its1986 report that the company wanted to achieve the same levelof US investments it had before it divested its fibre firmAmerican Enka in December 1985, when US investments represented20 pct of Akzo's total capital.   The US expansion plans were not an attempt to compensate forlosses in guilder income through the lower dollar, Loudon said.    He said a more important factor was the speed of growth inthe US, adding "It's the largest industrial market in the world."But he said the company would also be looking at possibleacquisitions in Europe.    Despite its highly liquid cash flow, Akzo did not planacquisitions on a scale that would negatively influence thecompany's debt/equity ratio, Loudon said.   The chairman said in the past two years Akzo had spent 1.1billion guilders on acquisitions, of which nearly two thirdswere in the United States.REUTER...&#3;